#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:9
msgid "Available kernel variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:11
msgid ""
"The standard kernel in UCS 5.0 is based on the Linux kernel 4.19. In "
"principle, there are three different types of kernel packages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:14
msgid ""
"A *kernel image package* provides an executable kernel which can be "
"installed and started."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:17
msgid ""
"A *kernel source package* provides the source code for a kernel. From "
"this source, a tailor-made kernel can be created, and functions can be "
"activated or deactivated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:21
msgid ""
"A *kernel header package* provides interface information which is "
"required by external packages if these have to access kernel functions. "
"This information is usually necessary for compiling external kernel "
"drivers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:25
msgid ""
"Normally, the operation of a UCS system only requires the installation of"
" one kernel image package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:28
msgid ""
"Several kernel versions can be installed in parallel. This makes sure "
"that there is always an older version available to which can be reverted "
"in case of an error. So-called meta packages are available which always "
"refer to the kernel version currently recommended for UCS. In case of an "
"update, the new kernel version will be installed, making it possible to "
"keep the system up to date at any time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:38
msgid "Hardware drivers / kernel modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:40
msgid ""
"The boot process occurs in two steps using an initial RAM disk (*initrd* "
"for short). This is composed of an archive with further drivers and "
"programs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:43
msgid ""
"The GRUB boot manager (see :ref:`grub`) loads the kernel and the *initrd*"
" into the system memory, where the *initrd* archive is extracted and "
"mounted as a temporary root file system. The real root file system is "
"then mounted from this, before the temporary archive is removed and the "
"system start implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/configure-hardware.rst:48
msgid ""
"The drivers to be used are recognized automatically during system start "
"and loaded via the :program:`udev` device manager. At this point, the "
"necessary device links are also created under :file:`/dev/`. If drivers "
"are not recognized (which can occur if no respective hardware IDs are "
"registered or hardware is employed which cannot be recognized "
"automatically, e.g., ISA boards), kernel modules to be loaded can be "
"added via |UCSUCRV| :envvar:`kernel/modules`. If more than one kernel "
"module is to be loaded, these must be separated by a semicolon. The "
"|UCSUCRV| :envvar:`kernel/blacklist` can be used to configure a list of "
"one or more kernel modules for which automatic loading should be "
"prevented. Multiple entries must also be separated by a semicolon."
