#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:58
msgid ""
"Part of the settings configured in |UCSUCR| are system-specific (e.g., "
"the computer name); many settings can, however, be used on more then one "
"computer. The |UCSUCR| policy in the domain administration UMC modules "
"can be used to compile variables and apply them on more than one "
"computer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:63
msgid ""
"The evaluation of the |UCSUCR| variables on a UCS system comprises four "
"stages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:65
msgid "First the local |UCSUCR| variables are evaluated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:67
msgid ""
"The local variables are overruled by policy variables which are usually "
"sourced from the directory service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:70
msgid ""
"The ``--schedule`` option is used to set local variables which are only "
"intended to apply for a certain period of time. This level of the "
"|UCSUCR| is reserved for local settings which are automated by time-"
"controlled mechanisms in |UCSUCS|."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:75
msgid ""
"When the ``--force`` option is used in setting a local variable, settings"
" adopted from the directory service and variables from the schedule level"
" are overruled and the given value for the local system fixed instead. An"
" example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:79
msgid "$ univention-config-registry set --force mail/messagesizelimit=1000000"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:83
msgid ""
"If a variable is set which is overwritten by a superordinate policy, a "
"warning message is given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:86
msgid ""
"The use of the |UCSUCR| policy is documented in the :ref:`ucr-templates-"
"policy`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:91
msgid "Using the |UCSUMC| module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:93
msgid ""
"The UMC module :guilabel:`Univention Configuration Registry` can be used "
"to display and adjust the variables of a system. There is also the "
"possibility of setting new variables using :guilabel:`Add new variable`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:97
msgid ""
"A search mask is displayed on the start page. All variables are "
"classified using a *Category*, for example all LDAP-specific settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:100
msgid ""
"The *Search attribute* can be entered as a filter in the search mask, "
"which can refer to the variable name, value or description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:103
msgid ""
"Following a successful search, the variables found are displayed in a "
"table with the variable name and the value. A detailed description of the"
" variable is displayed when moving the mouse cursor over the variable "
"name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:107
msgid ""
"A variable can be edited by clicking on its name. A variable can be "
"deleted by right-clicking and selecting :guilabel:`Delete`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:113
msgid "Using the command line front end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:117
msgid ""
"The command line interface of |UCSUCR| is run using the :command"
":`univention-config-registry` command. Alternatively, the short form "
":command:`ucr` can be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:124
msgid "Querying a UCR variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:128
msgid ""
"A single |UCSUCR| variable can be queried with the parameter "
":option:`get`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:131
msgid "$ univention-config-registry get ldap/server/ip"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:138
msgid ""
"The parameter :option:`dump` can also be used to display all currently "
"set variables:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:141
msgid "$ univention-config-registry dump"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:149
msgid "Setting UCR variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:153
msgid ""
"The parameter :option:`set` is used to set a variable. The variable can "
"be given any name consisting exclusively of letters, full stops, figures,"
" hyphens and forward slashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:157
msgid "$ univention-config-registry set VARIABLENAME=VALUE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:162
msgid ""
"If the variable already exists, the content is updated; otherwise, a new "
"entry is created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:165
msgid ""
"The syntax is not checked when a |UCSUCR| variable is set. The change to "
"a variable results in all configuration files for which the variable is "
"registered being rewritten immediately. The files in question are output "
"on the console."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:169
msgid ""
"In doing so it must be noted that although the configuration of a service"
" is updated, the service in question is not restarted automatically! The "
"restart must be performed manually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:173
msgid ""
"It is also possible to perform simultaneous changes to several variables "
"in one command line. If these refer to the same configuration file, the "
"file is only rewritten once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:177
msgid ""
"$ univention-config-registry set \\\n"
"> dns/forwarder1=192.0.2.2 \\\n"
"> sshd/xforwarding=\"no\" \\\n"
"> sshd/port=2222"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:184
msgid ""
"A conditional setting is also possible. For example, if a value should "
"only be saved in a |UCSUCR| variable when the variable does not yet "
"exist, this can be done by entering a question mark (``?``) instead of "
"the equals sign ( ``=``) when assigning values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:189
msgid "$ univention-config-registry set dns/forwarder1?192.0.2.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:197
msgid "Searching for variables and set values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:201
msgid ""
"The parameter :option:`search` can be used to search for a variable. This"
" command searches for variable names which contain ``nscd`` and displays "
"these with their current assignments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:205
msgid "$ univention-config-registry search nscd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:210
msgid ""
"Alternatively, searches can also be performed for set variable values. "
"This request searches for all variables set to ``primary.example.com``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:213
msgid "$ univention-config-registry search --value primary.example.com"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:218
msgid ""
"Search templates in the form of regular expressions can also be used in "
"the search. The complete format is documented at `Regular expression "
"operations in the Python 2 documentation <python2-re_>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:225
msgid "Deleting UCR variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:229
msgid ""
"The parameter :option:`unset` is used to delete a variable. The following"
" example deletes the variable :envvar:`dns/forwarder2`. It is also "
"possible here to specify several variables to be deleted:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:233
msgid "$ univention-config-registry unset dns/forwarder2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:241
msgid "Regeneration of configuration files from their template"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:245
msgid ""
"The parameter :option:`commit` is used to regenerate a configuration file"
" from its template. The name of the configuration file is entered as a "
"parameter, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:249
msgid "$ univention-config-registry commit /etc/samba/smb.conf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:254
msgid ""
"As UCR templates are generally regenerated automatically when UCR "
"variables are edited, this is primarily used for tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:257
msgid ""
"If no filename is given when running :command:`ucr commit`, all of the "
"files managed by |UCSUCR| will be regenerated from the templates. It is, "
"however, not generally necessary to regenerate all the configuration "
"files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:264
msgid "Sourcing variables in shell scripts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:268
msgid ""
"The parameter :option:`shell` is used to display |UCSUCR| variables and "
"their current assignments in a format that can be used in shell scripts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:271
msgid "$ univention-config-registry shell ldap/server/name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:276
msgid ""
"Different conversions are involved in this: forward slashes in variable "
"names are replaced with underscores and characters in the values which "
"have a particular significance in shell scripts are included in quotation"
" marks to ensure they are not altered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:281
msgid ""
"The |UCSUCR| output must be executed via the command :command:`eval` for "
"|UCSUCR| variables to be able to be read in a shell script as environment"
" variables:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:285
msgid ""
"# eval \"$(univention-config-registry shell ldap/server/name)\"\n"
"# echo \"$ldap_server_name\"\n"
"primary.firma.de"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:295
msgid "Policy-based configuration of UCR variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:297
msgid ""
"Part of the settings configured in |UCSUCR| are system-specific (e.g., "
"the computer name); many settings can, however, be used on more then one "
"computer. The *Univention Configuration Registry* policy managed in the "
"UMC module :guilabel:`Policies` can be used to compile variables and "
"apply them on more than one computer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:308
msgid "Policy-based configuration of the Apache start page and forced HTTPS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:310
msgid ""
"Firstly, a *Name* must be set for the policy which is to be created, "
"under which the variables will later be assigned to the individual "
"computer objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:313
msgid ""
"In addition, at least one *Variable* must be configured and a *Value* "
"assigned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:315
msgid ""
"This policy can then be assigned to a computer object or a container or "
"OU (see :ref:`central-policies-assign`). Note that the evaluation of "
"configured values differs from other policies: The values are not "
"forwarded directly to the computer, but rather written on the assigned "
"computer by Univention Directory Policy. The time interval used for this "
"is configured by the |UCSUCRV| :envvar:`ldap/policy/cron` and is set to "
"hourly as standard."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:326
msgid "Modifying UCR templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:328
msgid ""
"In the simplest case, a |UCSUCR| template is a copy of the original "
"configuration file in which the points at which the value of a variable "
"are to be used contain a reference to the variable name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:332
msgid ""
"Inline Python code can also be integrated for more complicated scenarios,"
" which then also allows more complicated constructions such as "
"conditional assignments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:338
msgid ""
"|UCSUCR| templates are included in the corresponding software packages as"
" configuration files. When packages are updated, a check is performed for"
" whether any changes have been made to the configuration files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:343
msgid ""
"If configuration files are no longer there in the form in which they were"
" delivered, they will not be overwritten. Instead a new version will be "
"created in the same directory with the ending :file:`.debian.dpkg-new`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:347
msgid ""
"If changes are to be made on the |UCSUCR| templates, these templates are "
"also not overwritten during the update and are instead re-saved in the "
"same directory with the ending :file:`.dpkg-new` or :file:`.dpkg-dist`. "
"Corresponding notes are written in the "
":file:`/var/log/univention/actualise.log` log file. This only occurs if "
"UCR templates have been locally modified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:354
msgid ""
"The UCR templates are stored in the "
":file:`/etc/univention/templates/files/` directory. The path to the "
"templates is the absolute path to the configuration file with the "
"prefixed path to the template directory. For example, the template for "
"the :file:`/etc/issue` configuration file can be found under "
":file:`/etc/univention/templates/files/etc/issue`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:360
msgid ""
"For the configuration files to be processed correctly by |UCSUCR| they "
"must be in UNIX format. If configuration files are edited in DOS or "
"Windows, for example, control characters are inserted to indicate line "
"breaks, which can disrupt the way |UCSUCR| uses the file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:368
msgid "Referencing of UCR variables in templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:370
msgid ""
"In the simplest case, a UCR variable can be directly referenced in the "
"template. The variable name framed by the string ``@%@`` represents the "
"wildcard. As an example the option for the activation of X11 forwarding "
"in the configuration file :file:`/etc/ssh/sshd_config` of the OpenSSH "
"server:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:375
msgid "X11Forwarding @%@sshd/xforwarding@%@"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:379
msgid ""
"Newly added references to UCR variables are automatically evaluated by "
"templates; additional registration is only required with the use of "
"inline Python code (see :ref:`ucr-templates-extend-python`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:386
msgid "Integration of inline Python code in templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:388
msgid ""
"Any type of Python code can be embedded in UCR templates by entering a "
"code block framed by the string ``@!@``. For example, these blocks can be"
" used to realize conditional requests so that when a parameter is changed"
" via a variable, further dependent settings are automatically adopted in "
"the configuration file. The following code sequence configures for "
"example network settings using the |UCSUCR| settings:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:395
#, python-format
msgid ""
"@!@\n"
"if configRegistry.get('apache2/ssl/certificate'):\n"
"    print('SSLCertificateFile %s' %\n"
"        configRegistry['apache2/ssl/certificate'])\n"
"@!@"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:404
msgid ""
"All the data output with the print function are written in the generated "
"configuration file. The data saved in |UCSUCR| can be requested via the "
"``ConfigRegistry`` object, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:408
msgid ""
"@!@\n"
"if configRegistry.get('version/version') and \\\n"
"        configRegistry.get('version/patchlevel'):\n"
"    print('UCS %(version/version)s-%(version/patchlevel)s' %\n"
"        configRegistry)\n"
"@!@"
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:418
msgid ""
"In contrast to directly referenced UCR variables (see :ref:`ucr-"
"templates-extend-simple`), variables accessed in inline Python code must "
"be explicitly registered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:422
msgid ""
"The |UCSUCR| variables used in the configuration files are registered in "
"*info* files in the :file:`/etc/univention/templates/info/` directory "
"which are usually named after the package name with the file ending "
":file:`.info`. If new Python code is entered into the templates or the "
"existing code changed in such a way that it requires additional or "
"different variables, one of the existing :file:`.info` files will need to"
" be modified or a new one added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../computers/ucr.rst:429
msgid ""
"Following the changing of :file:`.info` files, the :command:`ucr update` "
"command must be run."
msgstr ""

